If you're into hot cars and hot bods, this film series aims to please.  Full of adrenaline, action, horrible acting, and not enough bare skin, the films are a stereotypical thrill-ride of action, violence, and sexy people.  But there's nothing wrong with that at all ...


TRIVIA:
1.  For those interested, Tokyo Drift is the third film, but since we see that Han is alive and kicking at the beginning of Fast &amp; Furious, obviously the film precedes Tokyo Drift.  So if you're looking to watch the films in chronological order, be sure to watch Tokyo Drift LAST.
2.  Most people don't know, there's an extra minute of footage after the credits of the first film.
3.  When they arrived on set of the first film, neither Michelle Rodriguez nor Jordana Brewster had a driver's license or learner's permits.  
4.  For those who don't know, when Dom tells Brian at the house party, &quot;You can have any beer you want, as long as it's a Corona.&quot; ... this is a homage to Automotive Father, Henry Ford who is often credited with the phrase, &quot;You can have any color you want, as long as it's black.&quot;  Even though, the car he was referring to, the Model-T, actually came in several colors other than black, but black was by far the most common.
5.  To achieve maximum realism, the director of Tokyo Drift refused to use CGI &quot;drift-sequences&quot; and rather used professional drift and rally drivers to perform all of the drifting scenes.
6.  The yellow viper seen in 2 Fast 2 Furious was one of the first four &quot;new shape&quot; Production Dodge Vipers that the studio got &quot;on loan&quot; to use for shooting on the understanding they would not be damaged at all.  The Dodge Viper design and production team even sent representatives with each car and their presence was somewhat disruptive.  Because of this, the first car you see destroyed in the subsequent film is ... yes, a Dodge Viper.


